<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-219-802  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 219 802.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Forbes  March 19 1990 v145 n6 p172(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Free speech for phone companies? (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Huber, Peter.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The federal court of appeals in Washington, D.C.andP;  will decide inspring 1990 whether the regional Bell holding companies (RBHC)have the right to offer information services.andP;  ATandamp;T, the RBHCs andthe Justice Department are in favor of an electronic bill ofrights.andP;  The restriction of information services was added to thedivestiture decree that broke up ATandamp;T as an afterthought.andP;  TheAmerican Newspaper Publishers Association is opposed to allowingtelephone companies to engage in information services, fearingthat their lucrative revenues from classified ads will disappearif audiotex databases become easily accessible through telephonelines.andP;  If telephone companies do win the right to offerinformation services, it is likely that they will begin to acquireelectronic publishing and services companies and enter intocooperative agreements with companies such as Mead Data, Dow Jonesand Dun andamp; Bradstreet.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (rules and regulations).andO;Ticker:    T.andO;Statute:   United States Constitution. 1st Amendment (interpretation andconstruction).andO;Topic:     DeregulationGovernment RegulationInformation ServicesBell Regional Holding CompaniesLegal Issues.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>